==================================================================
Modifications by Dokkaebi
==================================================================

Dokkaebi adapts Zed into a Windows-focused terminal-centric workspace
optimized for AI coding agents (Claude Code, Gemini CLI, Codex, OpenCode)
and multi-tasking workflows. The major categories of modifications are:

1. Platform focus
   - Primary target reduced to Windows. Windows installer built via
     setup/dokkaebi.iss (Inno Setup), replacing upstream Zed's bundling
     pipeline.
   - macOS/Linux/FreeBSD-specific distribution assets and bundling
     scripts removed.

2. Application identity
   - Application renamed to "Dokkaebi" (crates/zed/Cargo.toml, build.rs,
     Windows resource metadata).
   - Custom application icon (crates/zed/resources/windows/app-icon-dokkaebi.ico).
   - About dialog credits upstream Zed explicitly.

3. New feature: Notepad panel
   - crates/notepad_panel: new crate providing an always-available
     scratchpad panel with right-click "send selected text to terminal"
     context menu.

4. GitHub releases-based auto-update
   - crates/github_update: GitHub Releases integration replacing Zed's
     proprietary update server, with user-visible AutoUpdateSetting toggle.

5. AI agent integration
   - AI coding agents (Claude Code / Gemini CLI / Codex / OpenCode) run as
     terminal sub-processes; original Zed assistant/agent crates retained
     for compatibility.

6. Localization
   - Korean (ko.json) and English (en.json) UI strings via i18n crate.
   - Installer messages in setup/messages/ (English; Inno Setup .isl format).

7. Repository cleanup
   - Upstream Zed's CI workflows, release pipelines, cloud/collab
     infrastructure, flatpak/snap packaging, macOS/Linux resources, and
     Zed Industries' SaaS legal documents (privacy-policy.md,
     subprocessors.md, terms.md, terms.rtf) have been removed as
     unused by Dokkaebi's build and distribution path.
   - legal/third-party-terms.md retained with wording adapted to
     Dokkaebi's context, to disclose acceptable-use policies of AI
     providers that users may connect to.

